data.content:
Your code already follows the recommended pattern perfectly:

- ✅ **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package adopted
- ✅ **`IFileSystem`** injected via constructor
- ✅ Calls go through `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText()` (not the static `File.ReadAllText`)

**There's nothing more to generate.** `System.IO.Abstractions` is the battle-tested, community-standard wrapper — a custom one would be redundant.

Just make sure you have these in place:

**DI registration** (in `Program.cs`):
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**Test helper** (in your test project):
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data.txt", new MockFileData("hello") }
});
var svc = new DataService(mockFs);
Assert.Equal("hello", svc.ReadData("/data.txt"));
```
